data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider has been on a path to **remove sync-over-async entirely**. In .NET 11, the opt-in you configured in .NET 10 (`EnableSyncOverAsync`) is **removed**. All synchronous LINQ operators against the Cosmos provider will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**Every call in your repository is affected:**

| Breaks | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated version

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `async Task<T>` return types, `await` every EF call
- Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)
- This is a **breaking change that cascades** — every caller up the chain must also become async (`async` controllers, middleware, etc.)
- `Add()` itself remains synchronous (it only tracks locally), but `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
